  "instruction": "Classify the given text into one of these categories: anger, fear, joy, love, sadness, surprise.\n\nImportant guidelines:\n- Focus on the explicit emotional content and tone of the text, not just individual trigger words\n- \"Upset\" or \"disappointed\" feelings can indicate surprise rather than anger, especially when discussing unexpected situations or impressions\n- Expressions like \"i feel\" or \"feel though\" followed by concerns or warnings (e.g., \"dangerous,\" \"risky\") often indicate anger or concern rather than fear, particularly when critiquing strategies, approaches, or behaviors\n- Fear typically involves personal anxiety or worry about one's own safety or outcomes\n- Anger typically involves frustration, criticism, or disapproval directed at actions, people, or situations\n- Consider the overall context: is the speaker expressing personal dread (fear) or expressing critical judgment about something being wrong or problematic (anger)?\n- Pay attention to the broader sentiment and communicative intent rather than isolated keywords"
